HTML (HyperText Markup Language)  
Used for: Structuring web pages.
Common Tags:  
  - Headings: <h1> to <h6>  
  - Paragraph: <p>  
  - Links: <a href="url">Click Here</a>
  - Images: <img src="image.jpg" alt="description">  
  - Lists: <ul> (unordered), <ol> (ordered), <li> (list items)  
  - Tables: <table>, <tr>, <td>
  - Forms: <form>, <input>, <button>, <textarea>  

CSS (Cascading Style Sheets)  
Used for: Styling web pages.  
Types of CSS:
Inline: style="color: red;"  
Internal: Inside <style> in the <head> section  
External: Linked using <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">  

CSS Selectors  
Element Selector: h1 { color: red; }  
Class Selector: .myClass { font-size: 20px; }  
ID Selector: #myId { background-color: yellow; }  

Box Model  
Elements in CSS have:  
Margin (outer space)  
Border (surrounding the content)  
Padding (inner space)  
Content (text, images, etc.)  

Responsive Design:  
Media Queries allow different styles for different screen sizes.  
Flexbox & Grid are used for layout management. 

Bootstrap 
is a popular CSS framework used to create responsive and mobile-first websites quickly. It includes predefined CSS classes, components, and JavaScript plugins.  
Getting Started with Bootstrap  
- Bootstrap can be included via CDN or installed using npm.  
- It provides a standardized way to design web pages without writing much CSS.  
Bootstrap Components  
- Buttons: Pre-styled buttons in different colors and sizes.  
- Navbar: A responsive navigation bar that collapses on smaller screens.  
- Cards: A flexible content container with an image, title, text, and buttons.  
- Forms: Pre-styled input fields, checkboxes, radio buttons, and submit buttons.  
- Bootstrap ensures that websites look good on all screen sizes.  
- It includes visibility classes to show or hide elements based on screen size.  
- Images and other elements automatically adjust to different devices.  
